VALUES
(40, 22, 5, 62, 2, 15, 16, 'went their ways, one to his farm', 'Distraction from Spiritual Priorities', 'This connection highlights the theme of prioritizing worldly concerns over spiritual obligations. Both passages emphasize the danger of being consumed by earthly pursuits, as seen in the actions of those who went to their farm and merchandise in Matthew, paralleling the admonition against loving the world in 1 John.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 5, 1, 19, 14, 14, 'made light of it', 'Indifference to Urgent Warnings', 'This connection highlights the theme of indifference to urgent warnings. In both passages, individuals dismiss critical messages, with the people in Matthew choosing their personal pursuits and Lot''s sons-in-law mocking his warning.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 5, 1, 25, 34, 34, NULL, 'Disregard for Spiritual Value', 'This connection highlights the theme of individuals prioritizing earthly concerns over spiritual significance. In both passages, characters choose immediate, tangible pursuits—farming and merchandise in Matthew, and a meal in Genesis—over their greater spiritual responsibilities.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 5, 19, 106, 24, 25, 'made light of it', 'Despisal of God''s Invitation', 'Both passages emphasize a disregard for God''s call. In Matthew, individuals prioritize their own interests, while in Psalms, the people despise the land and do not heed God''s voice.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 5, 20, 1, 7, 7, 'made light of it', 'Foolishness and Disregard for Wisdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of foolishness in both passages. In Matthew, those who made light of the invitation represent a disregard for wisdom, paralleling the fools in Proverbs who despise instruction.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 6, 43, 15, 19, 20, 'slew them', 'Persecution of Servants Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the mistreatment of servants. In Matthew, the servants are slain, while in John, Jesus warns that His followers will also face persecution. This connection highlights the shared theme of hostility towards those sent by God.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 6, 40, 5, 10, 12, 'slew them', 'Persecution for Righteousness', 'Both passages emphasize the theme of persecution faced by those who stand for righteousness. In Matthew 22:6, the servants are mistreated and killed, paralleling the blessedness of those persecuted in Matthew 5:10-12 for righteousness'' sake.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 6, 40, 10, 12, 18, 'slew them', 'Persecution of Servants', 'Both passages emphasize the rejection and mistreatment of messengers. In Matthew 22:6, the servants are slain, while Matthew 10:17 warns of being delivered up and scourged.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 6, 43, 16, 2, 3, 'slew them', 'Persecution of God''s Servants', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by God''s servants. Both passages emphasize the violent rejection of those sent by God, illustrating a continuity in the experience of suffering for faith.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 6, 44, 4, 1, 3, 'slew them', 'Rejection of God''s Messengers', 'This connection highlights the theme of rejection faced by God''s messengers. In Matthew, the servants are mistreated and killed, paralleling the treatment of the apostles in Acts who are seized and imprisoned for preaching.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 6, 44, 5, 40, 41, 'slew them', 'Suffering for Righteousness', 'This connection highlights the theme of suffering for God''s messengers. Both passages emphasize the mistreatment of servants and apostles, illustrating a continuity in the rejection of those who proclaim God''s message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 6, 52, 2, 14, 15, 'slew them', 'Persecution of God''s Servants', 'This connection highlights the theme of persecution faced by God''s messengers. Both passages emphasize the violent treatment of servants and prophets, illustrating a pattern of rejection and hostility towards those who deliver God''s message.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 7, 42, 19, 27, 27, 'destroyed those murderers, and burned up their city', 'Divine Judgment on Rejection', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment against those who reject authority. Both passages emphasize the consequences of refusing to accept the king''s rule, culminating in destruction and punishment.', 'theme', 0.34199999999999997, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 7, 60, 4, 17, 18, 'destroyed those murderers, and burned up their city', 'Judgment and Destruction Theme', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment and destruction for those who reject God''s message. Both passages emphasize the consequences faced by the unrighteous, with Matthew depicting the destruction of a city and 1 Peter warning of judgment beginning at the house of God.', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 7, 29, 2, 25, 25, NULL, 'Divine Judgment and Restoration', 'This connection highlights the theme of divine judgment in Matthew, where the king destroys the city, and the promise of restoration in Joel, where God restores what has been lost. Both passages emphasize the role of God''s army in executing judgment and bringing renewal.', 'theme', 0.321, 'medium', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 7, 42, 21, 24, 24, 'burned up their city', 'Destruction of Jerusalem Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of judgment against Jerusalem. Both passages depict destruction and suffering inflicted upon the city and its people.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 7, 5, 28, 49, 68, 'destroyed those murderers, and burned up their city', 'Destruction and Judgment Themes', 'Both passages emphasize destruction as a consequence of disobedience. Matthew 22:7 describes the king''s wrath leading to the destruction of a city, paralleling Deuteronomy 28:49-68''s depiction of a nation bringing destruction upon Israel for failing to obey God''s laws.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 7, 23, 13, 2, 5, 'he was wroth: and he sent forth his armies', 'Divine Judgment and Destruction', 'Both passages emphasize divine anger leading to destruction. Matthew 22:7 describes the king''s wrath resulting in the burning of a city, while Isaiah 13:2-5 speaks of the Lord''s anger and the destruction of the land.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 7, 24, 51, 20, 23, 'destroyed those murderers, and burned up their city', 'Divine Judgment and Destruction', 'Both passages emphasize divine judgment resulting in destruction. Matthew 22:7 describes the king''s wrath leading to the destruction of a city, while Jeremiah 51:20-23 illustrates the breaking in pieces of nations and kingdoms as instruments of war.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 8, 44, 13, 46, 46, 'not worthy', 'Unworthiness and Rejection Theme', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of unworthiness in relation to the invitation to eternal life. In Matthew, those invited to the wedding are deemed ''not worthy,'' while in Acts, the Jews are described as judging themselves ''unworthy of everlasting life.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 8, 53, 1, 5, 5, 'were not worthy', 'Worthy of the Kingdom', 'This connection highlights the theme of worthiness in both passages. In Matthew, those invited to the wedding are deemed ''not worthy,'' while in 2 Thessalonians, believers are encouraged to be counted ''worthy of the kingdom of God.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 8, 66, 3, 4, 4, 'were not worthy', 'Worthy and Defiled Garments', 'This connection highlights the theme of worthiness in both passages. In Matthew, those invited to the wedding are deemed ''not worthy,'' while in Revelation, those who have not defiled their garments are considered ''worthy.''', 'theme', 0.32799999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 8, 42, 20, 35, 35, 'were not worthy', 'Worthy and Resurrection Themes', 'This connection highlights the concept of worthiness in both passages. Matthew discusses those who were invited but deemed unworthy, while Luke speaks of those accounted worthy to attain resurrection.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 8, 66, 22, 14, 14, 'were not worthy', 'Worthy and Commandments Connection', 'This connection highlights the theme of worthiness in both passages. In Matthew, those who were bidden were deemed ''not worthy,'' while Revelation emphasizes the blessings for those who follow ''his commandments,'' suggesting a link between worthiness and obedience.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 8, 40, 10, 11, 13, 'were not worthy', 'Worthy Invitations and Peace', 'This connection highlights the concept of worthiness in both passages. In Matthew 22:8, those invited to the wedding are deemed unworthy, while in Matthew 10:11-13, the disciples are instructed to seek out those who are worthy in the towns they visit.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 8, 40, 10, 37, 38, 'not worthy', 'Worthy of the Invitation', 'Both passages emphasize the concept of worthiness in relation to following Jesus. In Matthew 22:8, those who were invited to the wedding are deemed unworthy, while in Matthew 10:37-38, Jesus states that those who prioritize family over Him are not worthy of Him.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 9, 42, 14, 21, 24, 'Go ye therefore into the highways', 'Invitation to the Feast', 'Both passages emphasize the call to invite those from the highways and streets to a feast. This connection highlights the inclusivity of the invitation, extending beyond the initially invited guests.', 'theme', 0.33499999999999996, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 9, 20, 1, 20, 23, 'bid to the marriage', 'Invitation to Wisdom', 'This connection highlights the call to invite others, as seen in both passages. Matthew 22:9''s ''bid to the marriage'' parallels Proverbs 1:20''s ''Wisdom crieth without,'' emphasizing the active invitation to partake in wisdom.', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 9, 41, 16, 15, 16, 'Go ye therefore into the highways', 'Call to Evangelism', 'Both passages emphasize a directive to go out and reach others. Matthew 22:9''s call to ''bid to the marriage'' parallels Mark 16:15''s command to ''preach the gospel to every creature.''', 'theme', 0.321, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini'),
(40, 22, 9, 20, 8, 1, 5, 'bid to the marriage', 'Call to Wisdom and Invitation', 'This connection highlights the theme of calling and invitation found in both passages. In Matthew, the call to the marriage is directed to those on the highways, while in Proverbs, wisdom calls out to men at the high places and paths.', 'theme', 0.314, 'high', 'v1.2', 'gpt-4o-mini')
